The paper deals with the computational complexity of certifying the Restricted Isometry Property (RIP) of a matrix, which is a concept commonly used in compressed sensing and sparse recovery. This falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also uses techniques from graph theory, specifically Cheeger's inequality, which suggests a possible categorization under data structures (cs.DS). The problem of certifying RIP involves analyzing the behavior of a matrix, which can be computationally intensive, indicating a possible categorization under computational complexity (cs.CC) and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
